{{Infobox number | number = 229 | prime = yes }} '''229''' ('''two hundred [and] twenty-nine''') is the [[natural number]] following [[228 (number)|228]] and preceding [[230 (number)|230]].
It is a [[prime number]], and a [[regular prime]].<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber=A007703|name=Regular primes}}</ref> It is also a [[full reptend prime]], meaning that the decimal expansion of the [[unit fraction]] 1/229 repeats periodically with as long a period as possible.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber=A001913|name=Full reptend primes: primes with primitive root 10}}</ref> With [[227 (number)|227]] it is the larger of a pair of [[twin primes]],<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber=A006512|name=Greater of twin primes}}</ref> and it is also the start of a sequence of three consecutive [[Square-free integer|squarefree number]]s.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber=A007675|name=Numbers n such that n, n+1 and n+2 are squarefree}}</ref> It is the smallest prime that, when added to the reverse of its decimal representation, yields another prime: 229&nbsp;+&nbsp;922&nbsp;=&nbsp;1151.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber=A061783|name=Primes p such that p + (p reversed) is also a prime}}</ref>
There are 229 [[cyclic permutation]]s of the numbers from 1 to 7 in which none of the numbers is mapped to its successor (mod 7),<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber=A000757|name=Number of cyclic permutations of [n] with no i->i+1 (mod n)}}</ref> 229 [[rooted tree]] structures formed from nine [[carbon]] atoms,<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber=A000678|name=Number of carbon (rooted) trees with n carbon atoms = unordered 4-tuples of ternary trees}}</ref> and 229 [[Polygon triangulation|triangulations]] of a polygon formed by adding three vertices to each side of a triangle.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber=A087809|name=Number of triangulations (by Euclidean triangles) having 3+3n vertices of a triangle with each side subdivided by n additional points}}</ref> There are also 229 different [[projective configuration]]s of type (12<sub>3</sub>12<sub>3</sub>), in which twelve points and twelve lines meet with three lines through each of the points and three points on each of the lines,<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber=A001403|name=Number of combinatorial configurations of type (n_3)}}</ref> all of which may be realized by straight lines in the [[Euclidean plane]].<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber=A099999|name=Number of geometrical configurations of type (n_3)}}</ref><ref>{{citation | last = Gropp | first = Harald | doi = 10.1016/S0012-365X(96)00327-5 | issue = 1–3 | journal = [[Discrete Mathematics (journal)|Discrete Mathematics]] | pages = 137–151 | title = Configurations and their realization | volume = 174 | year = 1997}}.</ref>
The [[complete graph]] ''K''<sub>13</sub> has 229 [[crossing number (graph theory)|crossings]] in its straight-line drawing with the fewest possible crossings.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|sequencenumber=A014540|name=Rectilinear crossing number of complete graph on n nodes}}</ref><ref>{{citation | last1 = Aichholzer | first1 = Oswin | last2 = Krasser | first2 = Hannes | doi = 10.1016/j.comgeo.2005.07.005 | issue = 1 | journal = Computational Geometry | mr = 2264046 | pages = 2–15 | title = Abstract order type extension and new results on the rectilinear crossing number | volume = 36 | year = 2007}}.</ref>
