{{Infobox software | developer = Objectivity, Inc. | released = {{Start date|2010}}<!-- see https://twitter.com/infinitegraph/status/16889034183 --> | programming language = [[Java (programming language)|Java]], Core in [[C++]] | genre = [[Graph database]] | license = [[Trialware]] | status = Discontinued, in favor of ThingSpan | website = {{URL|objectivity.com/products/infinitegraph/}} }}
'''InfiniteGraph''' is an enterprise distributed [[graph database]] implemented in [[Java (programming language)|Java]], and is from a class of [[Nosql|NOSQL]] (or Not Only SQL) database technologies that focus on [[Graph (data structure)|graph data structures]]. Developers use Infinitegraph to find useful and often hidden relationships in highly connected [[big data]] sets.<ref name="dbta100">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dbta.com/Editorial/Think-About-It/DBTA-100-The-Companies-That-Matter-Most-in-Data-89876.aspx |title=DBTA 100: The Companies That Matter Most in Data |last=Joyce Wells |date=June 26, 2013 |publisher=Database Trends and Applications |access-date=September 8, 2014}}</ref> <ref name="sqlAlt">{{Cite web |url=http://readwrite.com/2011/08/24/the-other-non-sql-alternative |title=The Other Non-SQL Alternative |last=Scott M. Fulton |date=August 24, 2011 |publisher=Readwrite |access-date=September 8, 2014}}</ref> InfiniteGraph is cross-platform, scalable, cloud enabled, and is designed to handle very high throughput.<ref name="riseCloud">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dbta.com/Editorial/Think-About-It/The-Rise-of-the-Cloud-Database-88941.aspx |title=The Rise of the Cloud Database |date=May 7, 2013 |publisher=Readwrite |access-date=September 8, 2014}}</ref> <ref name="georgeTown">{{Cite web |url=http://www.gsnmagazine.com/node/29210?c=cyber_security |title=Georgetown University taps Objectivity for Big Data research |date=May 1, 2013 |publisher=Readwrite |access-date=September 8, 2014}}</ref> <ref name="ciscoBlg">{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.cisco.com/security/big-data-in-security-part-iii-graph-analytics/ |title=Big Data in Security – Part III: Graph Analytics |last=Levi Gundert |date=December 11, 2013 |publisher=Readwrite |access-date=September 8, 2014}}</ref>
InfiniteGraph is suited for applications and services that solve [[Graph theory|graph problems]] or answer questions such as "How am I connected to [[Six Degrees of Kevin Bacon|Kevin Bacon]]?" or "What are the cheapest roundtrip flights from California to New York with no more than 2 stops, at least 30 minutes between flights, and that depart at 8am Tuesday and return by 6pm Friday?"<ref name="techcrunch">{{Cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/08/16/infinitegraph-steps-out-of-beta-to-help-companies-identify-deep-relationships-in-large-data-sets/ |title=InfiniteGraph Steps Out Of Beta To Help Companies Identify Deep Relationships In Large Data Sets |last=Rip Empson |date=August 16, 2011 |website=TechCrunch |publisher=AOL |access-date=August 16, 2011}}</ref>
Adoption is seen in government, telco/networking, healthcare, cyber security, manufacturing, finance, CRM, and social networking applications.
==Features==
* API/Protocols: Java (core C++) * Graph Model: Labeled directed multigraph. An edge is a first-class entity with an identity independent of the vertices it connects. * Backup, including online incremental backup and full restore. * Concurrency: Update locking on subgraphs, concurrent non-blocking ingest. * Consistency: Flexible (from ACID to relaxed). * Distribution: Lock server and 64-bit object IDs support dynamic addressing space (with each federation capable of managing up to 65,535 individual databases and 10^24 bytes (one quadrillion gigabytes, or a yottabyte) of physical addressing space). * Processing: Multi-threaded. * Cloud enabled. * Query Methods: Traverser and graph navigation API, predicate language qualification, path pattern matching. * Parallel query support. * Visualization tool. * Schema: Supports schema-full plus provides a mechanism for attaching side data. * Transactions: Fully ACID. * Tinkerpop Blueprints and Gremlin support. * Talend output connector to InfiniteGraph. * Source: Proprietary, with open source extensions, integrated components, and third party connectors. * License Options: Flexible pricing and license options. * Platforms: Windows, Linux, and Mac with full interoperability.
==History== InfiniteGraph is produced by Objectivity, Inc. - a company that develops database technologies supporting large-scale, distributed data management, object persistence and relationship analytics.<ref name="ciscoBlg" /><ref name="techcrunch" /><ref name="451Group">{{Cite web |url=https://451research.com/report-short?entityId=66355 |title=Objectivity identifies use cases for its InfiniteGraph graph database unit |last=Matt Aslett |date=February 9, 2011 |publisher=The 451 Group |access-date=February 9, 2011}}</ref> InfiniteGraph was first released to the public in 2010 and the latest version (v3.3) was made available in June 2014.<ref name="rel3.3">{{Cite web |url=http://www.pressreleasepoint.com/achieve-greater-functionality-ease-use-and-even-faster-performance-infinitegraph-33 |title=ACHIEVE GREATER FUNCTIONALITY, EASE OF USE AND EVEN FASTER PERFORMANCE WITH INFINITEGRAPH 3.3 |last=PressReleasePoint |date=June 10, 2014 |publisher=PressReleasePoint |access-date=September 8, 2014}}</ref>
