'''Robert (Rob) D. Morris''' is a mathematician who works in [[combinatorics]], [[probability]], [[graph theory]] and [[Ramsey theory]]. He is a researcher at [[Instituto Nacional de Matemática Pura e Aplicada|IMPA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://impa.br/en_US/page-pessoas/robert-morris/|title=IMPA - Instituto Nacional de Matemática Pura e Aplicada|website=Impa.br|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>
In 2015, Morris was awarded the [[European Prize in Combinatorics]] for "his profound results in extremal and probabilistic combinatorics particularly for his result on independent sets in hypergraphs which found immediately several applications in additive number theory and combinatorics, such as the solution of old problem of [[Paul Erdős|Erdős]] and for establishing tight bounds for Ramsey numbers, and also on random [[cellular automata]] and [[Bootstrap percolation|bootstrap problems in percolation]]."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurocomb2015.b.uib.no/eurocomb/the-european-prize-in-combinatorics/|title=The European Prize in Combinatorics|website=Uib.no|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>
In 2016, he was one of the winners of the [[George Pólya Prize]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siam.org/prizes/sponsored/polyacomb.php|title=SIAM: George Pólya Prize in Combinatorics|website=Siam.org|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>
He graduated with a Ph.D. from [[The University of Memphis]] in 2006 under the supervision of [[Béla Bollobás]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=109705|title=The Mathematics Genealogy Project - Robert D. Morris|website=Nodak.edu|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>
He was awarded the 2018 [[Fulkerson Prize]].
