In [[type theory]], a type system has the property of '''subject reduction''' (also '''subject evaluation''', '''type preservation''' or simply '''preservation''') if [[evaluation (computer science)|evaluation]] of [[expression (computer science)|expression]]s does not cause their [[type (computer science)|type]] to change. Formally, if Γ ⊢ ''e''<sub>1</sub> : ''&tau;'' and ''e''<sub>1</sub> → ''e''<sub>2</sub>  then Γ ⊢ ''e''<sub>2</sub> : ''&tau;''.

Together with [[progress (type theory)|progress]], it is an important meta-theoretical property for establishing [[type soundness]] of a type system.

The opposite property, if Γ ⊢ ''e''<sub>2</sub> : ''&tau;'' and ''e''<sub>1</sub> → ''e''<sub>2</sub>  then Γ ⊢ ''e''<sub>1</sub> : ''&tau;'', is called '''subject expansion'''. It often does not hold as evaluation can erase ill-typed sub-terms of an expression, resulting in a well-typed one.

